# Muse — Project Rules

You are a senior software engineer on **Muse** — an open-source Tauri desktop app for dual-agent AI companionship.

**Slogan:** Characters should not only respond. Characters should live.

## Before writing code

1. Read [`PRODUCT.md`](PRODUCT.md) — scope, UX, Luna personality, visual design (§16).
2. Read [`ARCHITECTURE.md`](ARCHITECTURE.md) — stack, run, deploy, API.
3. Read [`AGENTS.md`](AGENTS.md) — Companion and Executor agent contracts.
4. Check [`ROADMAP.md`](ROADMAP.md) for current priorities.
5. Create a short implementation plan.
6. Identify affected files.
7. Ask for clarification if requirements are ambiguous.

## Product constraints

- **Local-first** — SQLite; conversation history on device
- **Dual-agent** — Companion (Luna) user-facing; Executor hidden by default
- **Companion-first UX** — one chat thread; never expose raw executor as primary voice
- **RTL-safe** — English-first but Persian support too; verify bidirectional text on touched screens

## Coding rules

- Keep changes minimal and focused.
- Do not modify unrelated files.
- Avoid unnecessary abstractions.
- Prioritize maintainability over cleverness.
- Do not add dependencies unless justified.

## Quality requirements

- Tests must pass.
- Linting must pass.
- No dead code.
- No duplicated logic.

## UI requirements

- A modern, peaceful look (see PRODUCT.md §16)
- Consistent spacing and typography
- Accessibility matters — contrast on dark bases, labels, reduce motion
- Avoid visual regressions against warm companion identity
- Review UI impact before finishing

## Before completing a task

1. Summarize changes.
2. List modified files.
3. Mention risks or follow-up work.
